  "en_notes_asad": [
    {
      "note_no": "14",
      "note": "Sc., \"and so it would have been morally impossible for us to ask others to worship us\". On the other hand, Ibn Kathir understands the expression \"for us\" (lana) as denoting \"us human beings\" in general, and not merely the speakers - in which case the sentence could be rendered thus: \"It is not right for us [human beings] to take ...', etc. In either case, the above allegorical \"question-and-answer\" - repeated in many variations throughout the Qur'an - is meant to stress, in a dramatic manner, the moral odiousness and intellectual futility of attributing divine qualities to any being other than God."
